npc/eko: This area is the Redirect Zone. Nothing here goes where it claims — and neither does your money.
npc/eko: Let me show you the one thing the apps never will: the actual numbers.
npc/eko: Every gambling game is set with a "house edge." The machine is programmed to pay back LESS than players put in. Always less.
npc/eko: Say a slot returns 90% over time. Put in Rp100,000 and, on average, Rp90,000 comes back. The missing Rp10,000 is the house's guaranteed cut — on every spin.
npc/eko: "But I've seen people win!" A few, sometimes, briefly. That win is paid for by everyone else's losses — and it's dangled in front of you to keep you spinning.
npc/eko: Here's the cruel part: the longer you play, the more certain you lose. Play long enough and the math drags your balance to zero. That is not bad luck. That is arithmetic.
npc/eko: The "near win" — almost, so close, one more try — is engineered to feel like progress where there is none.
npc/eko: So weigh it honestly: what you can win is small and rare; what you can lose is everything, and near-certain. The money out is never worth the money in.
npc/eko: The algorithm running this learned from millions of losers exactly how to make you one too.
npc/eko: Clear eyes. Keep moving forward.
